While the model-averaged Bayesian t tests allow for more rich and robust inferences on the running example of Pleasant and Barclay (2018), the conclusions regarding the mean difference remained similar regardless of the type of test used. In this section, we introduce an additional example, which underscores how the new model-averaged t tests can lead to substantially different conclusions for widely used behavioral interventions. Roozenbeek et al. (2021) conducted a study to test the effectiveness of an accuracy nudge intervention. This study was a direct preregistered replication of Pennycook et al. (2020).8 The intervention involved asking participants the question, “To the best of your knowledge, is the above headline accurate?”.Fig. 15
